fields.name: Carman Ranch
fields.description: Operating from our fourth generation ranch at the base of the beautiful Wallowa Mountains in remote Northeastern Oregon, we focus on ranching practices that restore the soil, respect the animals, build sustainable businesses in our rural community, and grow nutrient dense, delicious food.

fields.name: Crown C Farms
fields.description: A specialty vegetable farm growing for 15 years, offering produce to seven grocery stores and three farmer stands. Crown C is a family farm.
fields.notes:
Notes on delivery: Prefers self-delivery. Aloha Produce will deliver for Redmond schools.
Notes on delivery minimums: Depends on co-delivery options in the same town/area; smaller amounts are possible.

fields.name: Barley Beef
fields.description: Barley Beef is raised on grass/hay and the leftover beer mash from local breweries. Beef is offered as ground – fresh or frozen, bulk or patty.

fields.name: Pat~n~Tams Beef
fields.description: Grass-fed meats

fields.name: Mahonia Gardens
fields.outreachConductor: Laurie, High Desert Food & Farm Alliance
fields.description: Vegetables and herbs of exceptional quality grown in Sisters, Oregon. We use only organic practices and emphasize biodiversity on our farm.
fields.notes: Growing on one acre, not a huge capacity to expand but could contract grow for a smaller school. Prefer to work with Agricultural Connections [to distribute], but could deliver in the right situation. No minimum through Ag connections; for direct local delivery $100.

fields.name: Seed to Table Farm
fields.outreachConductor: Laurie, High Desert Food & Farm Alliance
fields.description: Seed to table is a 2 acre non-profit educational farm.  Their mission is to increase health and wellness of students and families, specifically decreasing obesity, in the Sisters community through providing equal access to nutritious foods and offering opportunities in garden-based wellness education.
fields.notes: Email preferred.

fields.name: Sakari Farms
fields.outreachConductor: Laurie, High Desert Food & Farm Alliance
fields.description: Sakari Farms is located in the Tumalo, the heart of Central Oregon.  Our farm works in collaboration with the Central Oregon Seed Exchange as a unique Deschutes County based cold climate seed bank, offering free seed and agricultural education to the public.  We also host Sakari Botanicals, our Value Added Product culinary and healing tribal business.  Sakari Farms is unique in that we grow Native American Tribal Foods, offer on-farm Technical Assistance through our on-farm classes, and implement research based tribal seed production, contract and wholesale growing.  Our current growing creations consist of specialty tribal peppers, tomatoes, herbs and one of a kind native flowers.
fields.notes: Interested in demand planning and will work with districts to grow what is needed.

fields.name: Boundless Farmstead
fields.outreachConductor: Laurie, High Desert Food & Farm Alliance
fields.description: Boundless Farmstead uses sustainable practices to grow wholesale and retail vegetables, poultry, and eggs in Central Oregon.
fields.notes: Delivery/order minimum: in Bend $50, outside $200. Open to contract farming. Grow on 5 acres, 500 heads of leytuce a week, 15-20k lbs of onions 5k lbs of cabbage.

fields.name: Moon River Farm
fields.description: Moon River Farm is a small vegetable farm in Nehalem, OR. We grow vegetable varieties bred for flavor and vigor in our unique coastal climate.

fields.name: Port Orford Sustainable Seafood
fields.description: 100% traceability of species, boat and fisherman. Hook and line caught fish on family-owned day boats, delivered directly to the consumer.

fields.name: Estill Farms LLC
fields.description: Estill Farms has both a conventional blueberry farm in Drain, and a USDA/ODA Certified Organic blueberry farm near Scottsburg.
fields.notes:
100 lb delivery/order minimum if outside of Douglas, Coos or Lane counties. No minimum if within these counties.

Have sold for the past 2 years to Rosebug, South Umpqua, Winston Dillard, Glide, Sutherlin, Elkton. They have recently acquired Milton Freewater.

fields.name: Valley Flora
fields.description: Valley Flora is a diversified fresh market farm nestled on the banks of Floras Creek near Langlois, Oregon. We produce over 100 varieties of vegetables, berries and fruit to feed our local coastal community year-round. The farm was founded in 1998 based on a deep commitment to ecological and organic farming practices - relying on draft horse power, regenerative soil stewardship, and solar power to grow good food for Oregon’s south coast.
fields.notes:
Produces vegetables, fruits, and berries, see weekly fresh sheet for specifics.

Open to contract growing specific crops for fall/winter/spring production, such as root crops (carrots, beets, potatoes, etc).

fields.name: Lenhe Farms
fields.description: We are a 3rd generation farm growing over 100 types of seasonal vegetables on a year round basis. We have several acres of fruit with many different varieties of apples, pears, peaches, Asian pears, and nectarines. We attend 3 farmers markets a week: Coos bay (Wednesdays) Bandon (Fridays) and Umpqua Valley/Roseburg (Saturdays).
fields.notes: Delivery/order minimum varies. We offer a 20% discount to all our institutional and business buyers. While we grow year round we need to know projected demands to ensure we plant enough.

fields.name: Valadez Organic Produce
fields.description: We are certified Organic and Gap Certified. We are a family run farm who believe in teaching our kids where our food comes from.
fields.notes: Have not sold to schools before so not 100% sure they are school ready, but interested in prospect & being part of the Portal.

fields.name: Aichele Farms
fields.notes: Delivery/order minimum is 4 flats.

fields.name: Key Family Fruit Farm
fields.notes: Delivery/order minimum 15 boxes.

fields.name: K & K Blueberries
fields.notes: Delivery/order minimum 50 lbs.

fields.name: Bud Rich Potato
fields.description: Bud Rich Potato is a large producer of fresh potatoes located in Hermiston, OR. This GAP-certified and veteran-owned farm grow Russet Norkotah potatoes for all regions of Oregon.

fields.name: Way of Life Farms
fields.notes: Has sold to hospitals before.

fields.name: Umpqua Dairy
fields.description: All of our products are from 100% Oregon cows processed right here in Roseburg, Oregon, for almost 90 years.  We receive fresh milk daily from family farms located throughout Oregon, giving you the better, fresher products. These family farms take pride in keeping their animals healthy and providing us with delicious tasting milk. Milk that is produced from cows not treated with rBST*/rBGH*, a synthetic growth hormone. Our goals are the same: to provide you with a nutritious food whose taste, purity and quality are unsurpassed.
fields.notes: Self-distribution in western Oregon and independent distribution partners in eastern Oregon.

fields.name: Hummingbird Wholesale
fields.description: Organic food manufacturer and distributor, focused on Pacific Northwest-Grown and Farm Direct relationships for beans, grains, nuts, seeds, dried fruits, honey, sweeteners, oils, nut butters (no peanuts), granolas and trail mixes.
fields.notes: Self-distribution in western Oregon, along I-5 and to the coast, and works with several other distributors to reach Bend and other areas.

fields.name: The Bread Stop
fields.description: We produce many varieties of bread products; from Sandwich breads and Bagels to Rolls, Burger Buns and Soft Pretzels. We make bread like homemade; without any additives, preservatives or artificial anything. Because we service a wide variety of customers, we have both organic and conventional ingredients on hand. All of our whole wheat products are produced using local organic whole wheat flour from Camas Country Mill. (see Camas Country Mill's website at https://www.camascountrymill.com/).
fields.notes: Self-delivery and private distribution to coast area.

fields.name: De Casa Fine Foods
fields.description: We are a processor of organic and natural foods.
fields.notes: Self-distribute to the Portland, Salem, Corvallis, Albany, Eugene/Springfield, and Bend areas. Rogue Natural Foods distributes to southern Oregon.

fields.name: Farmers Table Grapes
fields.description: Grow certified organic table grapes.

fields.name: Oregon Fruit Products
fields.description: We are a family owned business since 1935 that provides fruit in many formats to the market. Specialty Canned Fruit, Aseptically packed Fruit Puree's, as well as value added Frozen products. Please go to www.Oregonfruit.com  to learn more.

fields.name: Deck Family Farm
fields.description: We are a small family farm specializing in pasture raised meats and animal products, with certified organic 100% grass-fed beef, pasture raised pork and eggs, and 100% grass-fed lamb.
fields.notes: Delivery/order minimum is $100 for Lane County deliveries, $200 for Multnomah County deliveries.

fields.name: Casad Family Farms
fields.description: Here at Casad Family Farms we use Organic, Biodynamic, and Permaculture principals to sustainably steward our 85 acres of land in Jefferson County, Oregon. 65 acres of our total land uses North Unit Irrigation water rights which provides us with clean Deschutes Basin River water to irrigate our crops. We grow mixed vegetables and root crops for wholesale distribution to local restaurants and grocery stores and farmers markets.
fields.notes: Over 8 years of production experience in Central Oregon and 5 years selling at wholesale scale.

fields.name: Rainshadow Organics
fields.description: Rainshadow Organics is located fifteen miles Northeast of Sisters, Oregon where we have farmed and gardened for over twenty-five years. We have a full-diet farm with dozens of varieties of certified organic vegetables, herbs, berries, flowers, and grains on 80 acres. This includes whole wheat berries and fresh, stone-ground flour. We also offer pasture-raised, non-gmo fed pork, chicken, eggs, turkeys, and beef.
fields.notes: The delivery/order minimum is 25 lb bag/35 lb crates.

fields.name: Classic Foods
fields.description: We offer a wide variety of pasta, artisanal ravioli, tortellini and gnocchi all made in-house, in small batches by our talented staff. We strive to use local ingredients whenever possible.

fields.name: Roadrunner Pizza
fields.description: Fresh, natural rising pizza dough.
fields.notes: Order/delivery minimum is dependent on location in state.

fields.name: Hood River Organic
fields.description: HRO is based in the Hood River Valley. They grow some of their own crops and mushrooms, and also source from other farms to fulfill their CSA orders. Everything is certified Organic, and they have a fleet of sprinter van delivery vehicles.

fields.name: Stepping Stone Farm LLC
fields.description: A small, woman-owned diversified vegetable farm in Mosier.
fields.notes: Micaela is a very small scale farmer, but would be a good match for the new Wahtonka Charter School or for small purchases. She is super amazing and eager to help feed the kiddos in our community.

fields.name: Peachwood Orchard LLC
fields.notes: Delivery/order minimum is 100lbs.

fields.name: Fry Family Farm
fields.description: Suzi and Steve Fry started farming in the Rogue Valley in 1990. What was then a couple acres on Wagner Creek Road in Talent has expanded to more than 90 acres of vegetables, flowers and berries being grown in Talent, Phoenix, Medford and Ashland. Growing food organically was a way Suzi and Steve could raise their five daughters in a healthy environment, steward the land, and contribute to their community. The girls all grew up working on the farm, they all left and a couple came back. Together they grow some of the finest produce in the Rogue Valley and were leaders in being some of the first in Oregon to be certified as part of the USDA/DOD Unprocessed Fresh Fruits and Vegetables Pilot Program and are leaders in the Rogue Valley in selling healthy, organic vegetables to schools.
fields.notes: May be able to deliver to Grants Pass (Josephine Co).

fields.name: Ella Bella Farms
fields.description: Organic farmer with a large variety of crops, such as tomatoes, winter squash,melons, peppers, and more.

fields.name: Smith Frozen Foods
fields.description: Frozen processor of locally grown vegetables

fields.name: Meats / Meat Alternates
fields.description: Meats and meat alternates (M/MA) include meat, poultry, fish, cheese, yogurt, soy yogurt, dry beans and peas, whole eggs, tofu, tempeh, peanut butter or other nut or seed butters, and nuts and seeds. Child Nutrition Program operators must serve meals that contain the amount of M/MA required in the lunch and supper Meal Pattern Charts as found in the Resource Center. Program operators have the choice to serve a M/MA as one of the two components of a snack served in the NSLP, CACFP, or as part of the breakfast for the SBP and CACFP.

fields.name: Fruits
fields.description: Fruits that are fresh, frozen, dried, canned (packed in water, full-strength juice, or light syrup) and full-strength fruit juice may contribute toward the fruits requirement.

fields.name: Milk
fields.description: Fluid milk refers to pasteurized nonfat milk, low-fat milk (1%), reduced-fat milk (2%), whole milk, lactose-free milk, lactose-reduced milk, cultured milk, such as cultured buttermilk, cultured kefir milk, and cultured acidophilus milk, acidified milk, such as acidified kefir milk and acidified acidophilus milk, and Ultra High Temperature (UHT) milk, all of which meet State and local standards for such milk. The fluid milk must also contain vitamins A and D at levels specified by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration. Please note that not all fluid milks on this list apply to all Child Nutrition Programs, and some of the fluid milk may be flavored. Refer to the sections below for program-specific information related to the fluid milk requirement.

fields.name: Vegetables
fields.description: Vegetables are one of the required components of reimbursable meals in the National School Lunch Program (NSLP) and Child and Adult Care Food Program (CACFP). Vegetables may be served as part of a reimbursable meal for the School Breakfast Program (SBP) and the Summer Food Service Program (SFSP). They may also be served as part of the reimbursable snack for the NSLP Afterschool Snack Service. The meal pattern requirements are described in the Charts located in the Resource Center.

fields.name: Grains
fields.description:
All reimbursable meals offered in the National School Lunch Program (NSLP), School Breakfast Program (SBP), Child and Adult Care Food Program (CACFP), and Summer Food Service Program (SFSP) must include a grains food product. A reimbursable snack in the CACFP, SFSP, or the NSLP Afterschool Snack Service must include a creditable grain.

FNS meal pattern regulations establish the minimum serving size(s) of grains required for breakfasts, lunches, suppers, and snacks. Meal pattern charts for each of the Child Nutrition Programs are in the Resource Center. This section pertains to grains requirements in the NSLP, SBP, and CACFP. Please refer to Appendix E for grains requirements for the SFSP and NSLP Afterschool Snack Service.

fields.name: Other Foods
fields.description: The foods in this section do not meet the requirement for any component in the meal patterns. These items are included for your convenience since they are frequently used as condiments and seasonings to round out the meal, improve acceptability, and satisfy children’s or adults’ appetites. Child Nutrition Program operators may include these foods in small portions.
